<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="sec-derivApp-ww">
  <title>Additional Worked-Out Problems</title>


   <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivApp-motion">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivApp-motion"/> Motion in Physics</title>
 
      
<example xml:id="prob-motion-derivApp">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The position of a particle moving along a line is given by
    </p>

    <me>
      s(t) = 2t^3 - 9t^2 + 12t, \quad t \ge 0,
    </me>

    <p>
      where <m>s</m> is measured in meters and <m>t</m> in seconds.
    </p>

    <p>
      (a) Find all times when the velocity equals <m>0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) Determine whether the particle is moving to the right or to the left at <m>t = 3</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) Find all times when the particle has acceleration <m>6 \text{ m/sec}^2</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) The velocity is the derivative of the position function:
    </p>
    <me>
      v(t) = s'(t) = 6t^2 - 18t + 12.
    </me>
    <p>
      Setting the velocity equal to zero gives
    </p>
    <me>
      6t^2 - 18t + 12 = 0 \implies t^2 - 3t + 2 = 0 \implies (t-1)(t-2) = 0.
    </me>
    <p>
      Thus, the velocity equals zero at <m>t = 1</m> and <m>t = 2</m>.
    </p>
    <p> (b) To determine the direction of motion at <m>t = 3</m>, we can evaluate the velocity at <m>t = 3</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      v(3) = 6(3)^2 - 18(3) + 12 = 54 - 54 + 12 = 12.
    </me>
    <p>
      Since <m>v(3) \geq 0</m>, the particle is moving to the right at <m>t = 3</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      (c) The acceleration is the derivative of the velocity function:
    </p>
    <me>
      a(t) = v'(t) = 12t - 18.
    </me>
    <p>
      Setting the acceleration equal to <m>6</m> gives
    </p>
    <me>
      12t - 18 = 6 \implies 12t = 24 \implies t = 2.
    </me>
    <p>
      So the particle has acceleration <m>6 \text{ m/sec}^2</m> at <m>t = 2</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="prob-motion-derivApp-maxHeight">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A particle moves vertically according to
      <m>s(t)=15t-at^2</m>,
      where <m>s</m> is measured in meters, <m>t</m> in seconds, and <m>a</m> is a positive constant.
    </p>

    <p>
      If the particle reaches maximum height at <m>t=3</m> seconds, find:
    </p>

    <p>
      (a) the value of <m>a</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) the maximum height reached.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) The velocity is the derivative of the position function:
    </p>
    <me>
      v(t) = s'(t) = 15 - 2at.
    </me>
    <p>
      Since the particle reaches maximum height at <m>t=3</m>, the velocity must equal zero at <m>t=3</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      v(3) = 15 - 2a(3) = 15 - 6a = 0 \implies 6a = 15 \implies a = \frac{5}{2}.
    </me>
    <p>
      (b) To find the maximum height, we can evaluate the position function at <m>t=3</m> using the value of <m>a</m> we just found:
    </p>
    <me>
      s(3) = 15(3) - \frac{5}{2}(3)^2 = 45 - \frac{5}{2}(9) = 45 - \frac{45}{2} = \frac{45}{2}  
    </me>
    <p>
      So the maximum height reached is <m>\frac{45}{2}</m> meters.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="prob-motion-derivApp-which-is-which">
    <statement>
    <p>
      One of the curves below represents the graph of a position function, and the other
      curve represents the graph of the corresponding velocity function.
      Which curve is which?
    </p>


      <image source="images/PositionVelocity.png" width="90%">
        <shortdescription>
          A graph with two curves (one solid red and one dashed blue) 
          plotted against time. The dashed curve has a local minimum and a local maximum, 
          while the solid curve crosses the t-axis at the same t-values where the dashed 
          curve has horizontal tangents.
        </shortdescription>
      </image>

  </statement>
 <solution>
    <p>
      First consider the possibility that the solid red curve is the graph of <m>y=s(t)</m>.
      If that is the case, then the graph of the derivative (the velocity function) <m>y=s'(t)</m> must satisfy:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The graph of <m>y=s'(t)</m> must pass through <m>(0,0)</m>, since the solid red curve has a horizontal tangent at <m>t=0</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The graph of <m>y=s'(t)</m> must be above the <m>t</m>-axis for <m>t&lt;0</m>, since the solid red curve is increasing there.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The graph of <m>y=s'(t)</m> must be below the <m>t</m>-axis for <m>t&gt;0</m>, since the solid red curve is decreasing there.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Although the dashed blue curve may pass through <m>(0,0)</m>, the rest of these sign conditions do not match it.
      Therefore, the solid red curve cannot be <m>s(t)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Next, assume the dashed blue curve is the position function <m>y=s(t)</m>.
      Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be the <m>t</m>-values where the dashed blue curve has its local minimum and local maximum, respectively.
      Then the derivative (the velocity function) <m>y=s'(t)</m> must satisfy:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The graph of <m>y=s'(t)</m> must cross the <m>t</m>-axis at <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=b</m>, since the dashed blue curve has horizontal tangents at those points.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The graph of <m>y=s'(t)</m> must be above the <m>t</m>-axis on <m>(a,b)</m>, since the dashed blue curve is increasing there.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The graph of <m>y=s'(t)</m> must be below the <m>t</m>-axis for <m>t&lt;a</m> and for <m>t&gt;b</m>, since the dashed blue curve is decreasing on those intervals.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      This description matches the solid red curve. Therefore, the dashed blue curve is <m>y=s(t)</m> and the solid red curve is <m>y=s'(t)</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-velocity-graph-questions">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The graph below shows the velocity <m>v=f(t)</m> of a particle moving along a horizontal line
      for the open interval <m>(0,10)</m>.
    </p>


      <image source="images/Velocity02.png" width="90%">
        <shortdescription>
          A piecewise linear graph of velocity v versus time t on the interval (0,10). The graph is below the t-axis for early times,
          crosses v=0 at t=2, stays above the axis until t=7, lies on v=0 from t=7 to t=9, and then rises above the axis again from t=9 to t=10.
          Several corners indicate times where the slope changes abruptly.
        </shortdescription>
      </image>

    <p>
      (a) When does the particle move forward?
    </p>
    <p>
      (b) When does the particle slow down?
    </p>
    <p>
      (c) When is the particle’s acceleration positive?
    </p>
    <p>
      (d) When does the particle stand still for more than an instant?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) The particle moves forward when <m>v(t) &gt; 0</m>, meaning the velocity graph is above the <m>t</m>-axis.
      From the graph, this occurs on <m>(2,7)\cup(9,10)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) The particle slows down when its speed <m>|v(t)|</m> is decreasing.
      If <m>v(t) &gt; 0</m> (moving forward), slowing down means <m>v(t)</m> is decreasing, so <m>v'(t) &lt; 0</m>.
      If <m>v(t) &lt; 0</m> (moving backward), slowing down means <m>v(t)</m> is increasing toward zero, so <m>v'(t) &gt; 0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      From the graph, <m>v(t) &lt; 0</m> on <m>(0,2)</m> and the velocity is increasing there, so the particle slows down on <m>(0,2)</m>.
      Also, <m>v(t) &gt; 0</m> on <m>(2,7)</m> and the velocity is decreasing on <m>(6,7)</m>, so the particle slows down on <m>(6,7)</m>.
      Therefore, the particle slows down on <m>(0,2)\cup(6,7)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      At times where the velocity graph has corners, the derivative <m>v'(t)</m> (acceleration) is not defined, so those times should not be included.
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) The acceleration is positive when <m>v'(t) &gt; 0</m>, meaning the velocity graph has positive slope.
      From the graph, this occurs on <m>(0,4)\cup(9,10)</m> (excluding any corner points).
    </p>

    <p>
      (d) The particle stands still when <m>v(t)=0</m>. From the graph, this happens at <m>t=2</m> and for <m>t\in[7,9]</m>.
      Standing still for more than an instant means an interval of time, so the answer is <m>[7,9]</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

    </subsection>

   <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivApp-relatedRates">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivApp-related"/> Related Rates</title>

      
<example xml:id="ex-related-rates-circle-circumference">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A computer animator creates a circle for which the area of the circle
      increases at the rate of <m>2 \text{ mm}^2/\text{sec}</m>. Find the rate of
      change of the circumference of the circle at the time that the radius
      is <m>3</m> mm.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Let <m>A(t)</m>, <m>r(t)</m>, and <m>C(t)</m> denote the changing area,
      radius, and circumference of the circle at time <m>t</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      We are given the rate of change of the area:
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle A'(t)=2 \ \text{mm}^2/\text{sec}.
    </me>

    <p>
      We are also told that at a particular time, say <m>t=0</m>,
    </p>

    <me>
      r(0)=3 \ \text{mm}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Our goal is to determine

    <m>
      \displaystyle C'(0).
    </m>
  </p>
    <p>
      The circumference of a circle is related to the radius by
    </p>

    <me>
      C(t)=2\pi r(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>t</m> gives
    </p>

    <me>
      C'(t)=2\pi r'(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, at time <m>t^\*</m>,
    </p>

    <me>
      C'(0)=2\pi r'(0).
    </me>

    <p>
      To determine <m>r'(0)</m>, we relate the radius to the area.
      The area of a circle is
    </p>

    <me>
      A(t)=\pi r^2(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Differentiating with respect to <m>t</m>,
    </p>

    <me>
      A'(t)=2\pi r(t) r'(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for <m>r'(t)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      r'(t)=\frac{A'(t)}{2\pi r(t)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Substitute the known values at <m>t=0</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      r'(0)=
      \frac{2}{2\pi \cdot 3}
      =
      \frac{1}{3\pi}
      \ \text{mm/sec}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Now substitute this into the expression for <m>C'(0)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      C'(0)
      =
      2\pi\left(\frac{1}{3\pi}\right)
      =
      \frac{2}{3}
      \ \text{mm/sec}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, when the radius is <m>3</m> mm, the circumference is
      increasing at a rate of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> mm/sec.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-related-rates-balloon">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A hot air balloon is released from its launching area and watched by a crowd in a viewing area
      <m>100</m> feet away from the launch site.
      What is the vertical speed of the balloon when its distance from the viewing area is
      <m>300</m> feet and that distance is increasing at a rate of
      <m>600</m> ft/hr?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Let <m>b(t)</m> denote the changing height of the balloon and
      let <m>c(t)</m> denote the changing distance from the balloon to the viewing area.
    </p>

    <p>
      At a particular instant, say <m>t=0</m>, we are given
    </p>

    <me>
      c(0) = 300 \text{ ft},
      \qquad
      c'(0) = 600 \text{ ft/hr}.
    </me>

    <p>
      We want to determine the vertical speed of the balloon at that time:
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle b'(0).
    </me>

    <p>
      The viewing area, launch site, and balloon form a right triangle.
      The base of the triangle is <m>100</m> ft, the height is <m>b(t)</m>,
      and the hypotenuse is <m>c(t)</m>. By the Pythagorean Theorem,
    </p>

    <me>
      100^2 + b^2(t) = c^2(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>t</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      2b(t)b'(t) = 2c(t)c'(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Solving for <m>b'(t)</m>,
    </p>

    <me>
      b'(t) = \frac{c(t)c'(t)}{b(t)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      To evaluate this at <m>t=0</m>, we still need the value of <m>b(0)</m>.
      Using the original relationship,
    </p>

    <me>
      100^2 + b^2(0) = c^2(0) = 300^2.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for the height:
    </p>

    <me>
      b(0) =
      \sqrt{300^2 - 100^2}
      =
      \sqrt{80000}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Now substitute the known quantities into the formula for <m>b'(0)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      b'(0) =
      \frac{300 \cdot 600}{\sqrt{80000}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Simplifying,
    </p>

    <me>
      b'(0) =
      \frac{180000}{200\sqrt{2}}
      =
      450\sqrt{2}
      \text{ ft/hr}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, when the balloon is <m>300</m> feet from the viewing area,
      its vertical speed is <m>450\sqrt{2}</m> ft/hr.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-related-rates-shadow-wall">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A spotlight is on the ground <m>20</m> ft away from a wall and a
      <m>6</m> ft tall person is walking toward the wall at a rate of
      <m>\frac{5}{2}</m> ft/sec.
    </p>

    <p>
      How fast is the height of the shadow changing when the person is
      <m>8</m> ft from the wall?
    </p>

        <image>
      <shortdescription>
        A spotlight on the ground shines toward a wall 20 feet away. A person
        stands between the spotlight and the wall, casting a shadow on the wall.
        The person is 6 feet tall. The distance from the spotlight to the person
        is labeled x, the distance from the person to the wall is 20 minus x,
        and the height of the shadow on the wall is labeled y.
      </shortdescription>
    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.35]
	
	% Ground and wall
	\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (22,0);
	\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,12) node[above] {Wall};
	
	% Key points
	\fill (20,0) circle (6.2pt) node[above right] {Spotlight};
	\fill (8,0) circle (6.2pt);
	\draw[thick] (8,0) -- (8,6) node[midway,right] {$6$};
	
	% Light ray and shadow
	\draw[thick] (20,0) -- (0,10);
	\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,10);
	
	% Distance labels
	\draw[<->] (0,-1.8) -- (20,-1.8) node[midway,fill=white,inner sep=2pt] {$20$};
	\draw[<->] (8,-0.9) -- (20,-0.9) node[midway,fill=white,inner sep=2pt] {$x$};
	\draw[<->] (0,-0.9) -- (8,-0.9) node[midway,fill=white,inner sep=2pt] {$20-x$};
	
	% Shadow height label
	\draw[<->] (-1.2,0) -- (-1.2,10) node[midway,fill=white,inner sep=2pt] {$y$};
	\draw[fill=black!70] (0,0) rectangle (3pt,10) node[rotate=90, pos=.5, below] {Shadow};

\end{tikzpicture}
 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>







  </statement>







  <solution>
    <p>
      Let
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><m>x(t)</m> be the distance of the person from the spotlight,</li>
      <li><m>z(t)</m> be the distance of the person from the wall, and</li>
      <li><m>y(t)</m> be the height of the shadow on the wall.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Because the wall is <m>20</m> ft from the spotlight,
    </p>

    <me>
      z(t)=20-x(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      The person is walking toward the wall at a rate of
      <m>\frac{5}{2}</m> ft/sec, so
    </p>

    <me>
      z'(t)=-\frac{5}{2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      At the instant of interest,
    </p>

    <me>
      z(0)=8,
      \qquad
      x(0)=20-8=12.
    </me>

    <p>
      We want to determine the rate of change of the height of the shadow:
    </p>

    <me>
      y'(0).
    </me>

    <p>
      From the geometry of the situation there are two similar triangles:
      the large triangle formed by the spotlight and the shadow on the wall,
      and the smaller triangle formed by the spotlight and the person.
      Using similar triangles,
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{y(t)}{6}=\frac{20}{x(t)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solving for <m>y(t)</m>,
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t)=\frac{120}{x(t)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Differentiate with respect to <m>t</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      y'(t)=-\frac{120}{x^2(t)}\,x'(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      To determine <m>x'(t)</m>, differentiate the relationship
      <m>x(t)=20-z(t)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      x'(t)=-z'(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>z'(t)=-\frac{5}{2}</m>,
    </p>

    <me>
      x'(t)=\frac{5}{2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Now evaluate the derivative when <m>x(0)=12</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      y'(0)
      =
      -\frac{120}{12^2}\left(\frac{5}{2}\right)
      =
      -\frac{25}{12}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore the height of the shadow is changing at a rate of
      <m>-\frac{25}{12}</m> ft/sec. The negative sign indicates that
      the height of the shadow is decreasing at that moment.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-related-rates-cylinder">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A flexible cylinder has been built which can change its volume by changing
      its height or its radius. However, design constraints require that its
      height is always twice its radius.
    </p>

    <p>
      Find the rate of change of the volume of the cylinder when its radius is
      <m>3</m> feet and the radius is increasing at a rate of
      <m>2</m> ft/min.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      Let <m>r(t)</m> denote the changing radius of the cylinder,
      <m>h(t)</m> denote the changing height, and
      <m>V(t)</m> denote the volume.
    </p>

    <p>
      We are given the design constraint
    </p>

    <me>
      h(t)=2r(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      At a particular time, say <m>t=0</m>,
    </p>

    <me>
      r(0)=3,
      \qquad
      r'(0)=2.
    </me>

    <p>
      We want to determine the rate of change of the volume at that same time:
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle V'(0).
    </me>

    <p>
      The volume of a cylinder is
    </p>

    <me>
      V(t)=\pi r^2(t)h(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Using the relationship <m>h(t)=2r(t)</m>, we can rewrite the volume in
      terms of the radius alone:
    </p>

    <me>
      V(t)=\pi r^2(t)\bigl(2r(t)\bigr)=2\pi r^3(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Differentiate with respect to <m>t</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      V'(t)=6\pi r^2(t)r'(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Now evaluate this derivative at <m>t=0</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      V'(0)
      =
      6\pi (3)^2(2)
      =
      108\pi.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, when the radius is <m>3</m> ft, the volume is increasing at a
      rate of
    </p>

    <me>
      108\pi \text{ ft}^3/\text{min}.
    </me>

  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-production-solar-panels">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A factory produces solar panels according to the production function
    </p>

    <me>
      S = 600L^{0.3}K^{0.6},
    </me>

    <p>
      where <m>L</m> represents thousands of dollars spent on labor and
      <m>K</m> represents thousands of dollars spent on equipment.
    </p>

    <p>
      (a) How many panels are produced when <m>L=100</m> and <m>K=81</m>?
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) The company keeps equipment spending fixed at <m>K=81</m>.
      At what rate is production changing with respect to labor spending
      when <m>L=100</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><alert>Part (a)</alert></p>

    <p>
      Substitute the given values into the production function.
    </p>

    <me>
      S = 600(100)^{0.3}(81)^{0.6}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Without a calculator we would leave the answer in this form, but since this is an example exercise we can compute the powers to get a numerical approximation.
    </p>


    <me>
      S \approx 33361.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the factory produces approximately <m>33361</m> solar panels.
    </p>


    <p><alert>Part (b)</alert></p>

    <p>
      Since equipment spending is fixed at <m>K=81</m>, we can plug that in, leaving our only variable <m>L</m>. 
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
S &amp; = &amp; 600L^{0.3}(81)^{0.6} \\
      \frac{ dS}{dL}
      &amp; = &amp; 
      600(0.3)L^{-0.7}(81)^{0.6}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Now evaluate at <m>L=100</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{ dS}{dL}
      =
      180(100)^{-0.7}(81)^{0.6}.
    </me>

    <p>
     Again, if we did not have access to a calculator this is how we would leave our final answer (WeBWorK would accept this as well).  
     However since this is an example exercise, we can compute the powers to get a numerical approximation.
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{ dS}{dL}
      \approx 100.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore production is increasing at approximately
      <m>100</m> panels per additional thousand dollars spent on labor.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>


    </subsection>


   <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivApp-linear">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivApp-linear"/> Linear Approximation and L'Hopital's Rule</title>

<example xml:id="ex-linearization-root-exp-sin">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The equation
    </p>

    <me>
      e^x + \sin x = 1.1
    </me>

    <p>
      has a solution near <m>x=0</m>.  
      Approximate this solution by replacing the left-hand side with its
      linearization at <m>x=0</m> and then solving the resulting equation.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      Let
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=e^x+\sin x.
    </me>

    <p>
      We approximate <m>f(x)</m> near <m>x=0</m> using its linearization
    </p>

    <me>
      L(x)=f(0)+f'(0)x.
    </me>

    <p>
      First compute the value of the function at <m>x=0</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      f(0)=e^0+\sin(0)=1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Next compute the derivative.
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(x)=e^x+\cos x.
    </me>

    <p>
      Evaluate the derivative at <m>x=0</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(0)=e^0+\cos(0)=1+1=2.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore the linearization of <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x=0</m> is
    </p>

    <me>
      L(x)=1+2x.
    </me>

    <p>
      We now approximate the equation
      <m>e^x+\sin x=1.1</m> by solving
    </p>

    <me>
      1+2x=1.1.
    </me>

    <me>
      2x=0.1.
    </me>

    <me>
      x=0.05.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus an approximate solution to the equation is
    </p>

    <me>
      x\approx 0.05.
    </me>

    <p>
      If we have access to technology, we can check how good this
      approximation is by evaluating the original expression
      <m>e^x+\sin x</m> at <m>x=0.05</m>.
      Doing so gives a value very close to <m>1.1</m>, confirming that
      the linear approximation produced a reasonable estimate.
    </p>

    <p>
      While this type of numerical check can be helpful for building
      intuition and verifying results, it is important to note that
      calculators may not be available on quizzes or exams.  In those
      situations the goal is simply to use linearization to produce a
      reasonable approximation based on calculus rather than numerical
      computation.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-linearization-battery-range">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A phone’s battery range <m>R(T)</m> (in hours) depends on temperature <m>T</m> (in degrees Fahrenheit).
      A test reports
      <m>R(70)=11.5</m>
      and
      <m>R(80)=10.8</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (a) Estimate <m>R'(70)</m> using the average rate of change from <m>T=70</m> to <m>T=80</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) Write the linear approximation to <m>R(T)</m> near <m>T=70</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) Use your linear approximation to estimate <m>R(74)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (d) Interpret the meaning of <m>R'(70)</m> in a sentence, including units.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      <alert>Part (a)</alert>:
      Use the slope of the secant line from <m>T=70</m> to <m>T=80</m> as an estimate for <m>R'(70)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle R'(70)\approx \frac{R(80)-R(70)}{80-70}
      =\frac{10.8-11.5}{10}
      =\frac{-0.7}{10}
      =-0.07.
    </me>

    <p>
      So <m>R'(70)\approx -0.07</m> hours per degree Fahrenheit.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Part (b)</alert>:
      The linearization (tangent line approximation) at <m>T=70</m> is
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle L(T)=R(70)+R'(70)(T-70).
    </me>

    <p>
      Using <m>R(70)=11.5</m> and our estimate <m>R'(70)\approx -0.07</m>, we get
    </p>

    <me>
      \displaystyle L(T)=11.5-0.07(T-70).
    </me>

    <p>
      <alert>Part (c)</alert>: 
      Estimate <m>R(74)</m> by evaluating <m>L(74)</m>:
    </p>

    <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
      \displaystyle R(74) \amp \approx \amp L(74)\\
      \amp \approx \amp 11.5-0.07(74-70)\\
      \amp \approx \amp 11.5-0.07(4)\\
      \amp \approx \amp 11.5-0.28\\
      \amp \approx \amp 11.22.
    \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      So the battery range at <m>74^\circ</m>F is approximately <m>11.22</m> hours.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Part (d)</alert>: 
      The value <m>R'(70)\approx -0.07</m> hours per <m>^\circ</m>F means that near
      <m>70^\circ</m>F, increasing the temperature by <m>1^\circ</m>F decreases the battery range by about
      <m>0.07</m> hours (about <m>4.2</m> minutes).
    </p>



  </solution>
</example>




    </subsection> 
   

       <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivApp-extrema">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivApp-extrema"/> Extrema</title>


<example xml:id="ex-critical-numbers-radical">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find all critical numbers of the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=\sqrt{x}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{x}}.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      Recall that the <term>critical numbers</term> of a function are the
      values of <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m> for which either
      <m>f'(x)=0</m> or <m>f'(x)</m> is undefined.
    </p>

    <p>
      Rewrite the function using exponents:
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=x^{1/2}+x^{-1/2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Differentiate:
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f'(x)
    \amp= \frac{1}{2}x^{-1/2}-\frac{1}{2}x^{-3/2} \\
    \amp= \frac{1}{2x^{1/2}}-\frac{1}{2x^{3/2}}.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Finding a common denominator gives
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(x)=\frac{x-1}{2x^{3/2}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      To determine where <m>f'(x)=0</m>, set the numerator equal to zero:
    </p>

    <me>
      x-1=0.
    </me>

    <me>
      x=1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Next determine where the derivative is undefined by examining the
      denominator.  The denominator is zero when
    </p>

    <me>
      2x^{3/2}=0.
    </me>

    <me>
      x=0.
    </me>

    <p>
      However, the original function <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}+1/\sqrt{x}</m> is not
      defined at <m>x=0</m>, so this value is not in the domain of
      <m>f</m> and therefore cannot be a critical number.
    </p>

    <p>
      Thus the only critical number of the function is
    </p>

    <me>
      x=1.
    </me>

  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-critical-numbers-rational">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find all critical numbers of the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=\frac{2x}{(x^2+2)^2}.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Recall that the <term>critical numbers</term> of a function are the values of
      <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m> for which either <m>f'(x)=0</m> or
      <m>f'(x)</m> is undefined.
    </p>

    <p>
      We begin by computing the derivative using the quotient rule.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f'(x)
    \amp = \frac{(x^2+2)^2(2)-2x\left[2(x^2+2)(2x)\right]}{(x^2+2)^4} \\
    \amp = \frac{2(x^2+2)^2-8x^2(x^2+2)}{(x^2+2)^4}.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Factor the numerator.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f'(x)
    \amp = \frac{(x^2+2)\bigl[2(x^2+2)-8x^2\bigr]}{(x^2+2)^4} \\
    \amp = \frac{2(2-3x^2)}{(x^2+2)^3}.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      To find where <m>f'(x)=0</m>, we set the numerator equal to zero:
    </p>

    <me>
      2(2-3x^2)=0.
    </me>

    <me>
      2-3x^2=0.
    </me>

    <me>
      x^2=\frac{2}{3}.
    </me>

    <me>
      x=\pm\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Next we determine where the derivative is undefined by examining the denominator.
      The denominator is zero when
    </p>

    <me>
      (x^2+2)^3=0.
    </me>

    <p>
      However, <m>x^2+2&gt;0</m> for all real numbers <m>x</m>, so the denominator
      can never be zero. Therefore <m>f'(x)</m> is defined for all real <m>x</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Thus the critical numbers of <m>f(x)</m> are
    </p>

    <me>
      x=\pm\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}.
    </me>

  </solution>
</example>      


<example xml:id="ex-absolute-extrema-graph">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the graph of <m>f(x)</m> below on the interval <m>[0,5]</m>.
        </p>


 <image width="60%">
  <shortdescription>
    A graph of f(x) on a square grid from 0 to 5. Starting at (0,3), the function curves upward to a maximum at (1,4), then curves downward passing through (2,3) and reaching a minimum at (3,1). After x = 3, the graph is a straight line segment increasing to (5,5).
  </shortdescription>
    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}
	\draw[->, thick] (-.3,0) -- (5.3,0);
	\draw[->, thick] (0,-.3) -- (0,5.3);
	\draw[thin] (0,0) grid (5,5);
	\begin{scope}
		\clip (-.3,0) rectangle (5.3,5.3); 
		\draw[very thick] plot[domain=0:2, smooth] (\x, {4-(1-\x)^2});
		\draw[very thick] (2,3)-- (3,1) -- (5,5);
	
	\end{scope}
	\draw (4.5,2.5) node {$f(x)$};
	\foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5} {
		\draw (\x, 2pt) -- (\x, -2pt) node[font=\small, below] {\x};
		\draw (2pt, \x) -- ( -2pt, \x) node[font=\small, left] {\x};
		
	} 
\end{tikzpicture}
 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>

  <p> (a) Identify the critical numbers of <m>f</m> and explain how you know they are critical numbers.</p>
  <p> (b) Identify the absolute maximum and minimum values of <m>f</m> and the <m>x</m>-values where they occur.</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      <alert>Part (a)</alert>: The critical numbers of <m>f</m> are the values of <m>x</m> where the derivative is zero or undefined.  
      From the graph, we can see that the function has a horizontal tangent at <m>x=1</m> and a corner at <m>x=3</m>.  
      Therefore, the critical numbers of <m>f</m> are
    </p>

    <me>
      x=1 \text{ and } x=3.
    </me>

    <p>
      <alert>Part (b)</alert>: The absolute maximum value of <m>f</m> on the interval <m>[0,5]</m> is <m>5</m>, 
      which occurs at <m>x=5</m>.  The absolute minimum value of <m>f</m> on the interval is <m>1</m>, which occurs at <m>x=3</m>.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-absolute-extrema-polynomial">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=\frac{2}{3}x^3-2x^2-6x+1, \qquad -2 \le x \le 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Determine the absolute maximum and minimum values of <m>f</m> and the
      <m>x</m>-values where these extrema occur.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      First determine the critical numbers of <m>f</m>.  Compute the derivative.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f'(x)
    \amp= \frac{2}{3}\cdot 3x^2 -4x -6 \\
    \amp= 2x^2-4x-6 \\
    \amp= 2(x^2-2x-3) \\
    \amp= 2(x-3)(x+1).
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Setting <m>f'(x)=0</m> gives
    </p>

    <me>
      2(x-3)(x+1)=0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the critical numbers are
    </p>

    <me>
      x=-1, \quad x=3.
    </me>

    <p>
      To determine the absolute extrema on the interval <m>[-2,1]</m>, we
      evaluate <m>f</m> at the endpoints and at any critical numbers inside
      the interval.  Since <m>x=3</m> lies outside the interval, we only
      check <m>x=-2</m>, <m>x=1</m>, and <m>x=-1</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f(-2) \amp= \frac{2}{3}(-2)^3-2(-2)^2-6(-2)+1
           = -\frac{1}{3} \\[6pt]
    f(1) \amp= \frac{2}{3}(1)^3-2(1)^2-6(1)+1
          = -\frac{19}{3} \\[6pt]
    f(-1) \amp= \frac{2}{3}(-1)^3-2(-1)^2-6(-1)+1
           = \frac{13}{3}.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Comparing these values, the absolute maximum value of <m>f</m> is 
      <m> \frac{13}{3},
    </m>
      which occurs at <m>x=-1</m>.  </p> 
      <p> 
        The absolute minimum value of <m>f</m> is
    <m>
      -\frac{19}{3},
    </m>
      which occurs at <m>x=1</m>.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-absolute-extrema-abs">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=|x-2|, \qquad 0 \le x \le 5.
    </me>

    <p>
      Determine the absolute maximum and minimum values of <m>f</m> and the
      <m>x</m>-values where these extrema occur.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      When a function involves absolute values, it is often helpful to rewrite it
      using the definition of absolute value:
    </p>

    <me>
    |A|=
    \begin{cases}
    -A, &amp; A\lt 0 \\
    A, &amp; A\ge 0
    \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      For this function,
    </p>

    <me>
    f(x)=|x-2|=
    \begin{cases}
    -(x-2), &amp; x\lt 2 \\
    x-2, &amp; x\ge 2
    \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      Taking derivatives of each piece gives
    </p>

    <me>
    f'(x)=
    \begin{cases}
    -1, &amp; x\lt 2 \\
    1, &amp; x\gt 2
    \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      The derivative at <m>x=2</m> is undefined.  Indeed,
    </p>

    <me>
    f'(2)=
    \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{|(2+h)-2|-|2-2|}{h}
    =
    \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{|h|}{h},
    </me>

    <p>
      and this limit does not exist.  Thus the only critical number is
    </p>

    <me>
    x=2.
    </me>

    <p>
      To determine the absolute extrema on the interval
      <m>[0,5]</m>, evaluate <m>f</m> at the critical number and the endpoints.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f(0) \amp= |0-2| = 2 \\
    f(2) \amp= |2-2| = 0 \\
    f(5) \amp= |5-2| = 3
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, the absolute maximum value of <m>f</m> is
      <m>3</m>, which occurs at <m>x=5</m>.
      The absolute minimum value of <m>f</m> is
      <m>0</m>, which occurs at <m>x=2</m>.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-absolute-extrema-fractional-power">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=x+3x^{2/3}, \qquad -1 \le x \le 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Determine the absolute maximum and minimum values of <m>f</m> and the
      <m>x</m>-values where these extrema occur.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      First determine the critical numbers of <m>f</m>.  Compute the derivative.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f'(x)
    \amp= 1 + 3\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)x^{-1/3} \\
    \amp= 1 + 2x^{-1/3} \\
    \amp= 1 + \frac{2}{x^{1/3}}.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      To determine where <m>f'(x)=0</m>, solve
    </p>

    <me>
      1+\frac{2}{x^{1/3}}=0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Multiply both sides by <m>x^{1/3}</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      x^{1/3}+2=0.
    </me>

    <me>
      x^{1/3}=-2.
    </me>

    <me>
      x=(-2)^3=-8.
    </me>

    <p>
      Next determine where the derivative is undefined.  The derivative
      <m>f'(x)=1+\frac{2}{x^{1/3}}</m> is undefined when
    </p>

    <me>
      x^{1/3}=0.
    </me>

    <me>
      x=0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the critical numbers are <m>x=-8</m> and <m>x=0</m>.
      However, only <m>x=0</m> lies in the interval <m>[-1,1]</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      To determine the absolute extrema on <m>[-1,1]</m>, evaluate
      <m>f</m> at the endpoints and the critical number in the interval.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f(-1) \amp= -1 + 3(-1)^{2/3}
            = -1 + 3(1)
            = 2 \\[6pt]
    f(1) \amp= 1 + 3(1)^{2/3}
           = 1 + 3
           = 4 \\[6pt]
    f(0) \amp= 0 + 3(0)^{2/3}
           = 0.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Comparing these values, the absolute maximum value of <m>f</m> is
      <m>4</m>, which occurs at <m>x=1</m>.
      The absolute minimum value of <m>f</m> is <m>0</m>, which occurs at
      <m>x=0</m>.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>



    </subsection>


       <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivApp-mvt">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivApp-mvt"/> Mean Value Theorem</title>

      
<example xml:id="ex-rolles-theorem-cubic">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=x^3-x+2
    </me>

    <p>
      on the interval <m>[0,1]</m> satisfies the conditions of Rolle’s
      Theorem. Then find a value <m>c\in(0,1)</m> for which <m>f'(c)=0</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      The function <m>f(x)=x^3-x+2</m> is a polynomial, so it is continuous
      for all real numbers and differentiable for all real numbers.
      Therefore it is continuous on the closed interval <m>[0,1]</m> and
      differentiable on the open interval <m>(0,1)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Next evaluate the function at the endpoints.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f(0) \amp= 0^3-0+2 = 2 \\
    f(1) \amp= 1^3-1+2 = 2.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>f(0)=f(1)</m>, all of the conditions of Rolle’s Theorem are
      satisfied. Therefore there must exist at least one
      <m>c\in(0,1)</m> such that
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(c)=0.
    </me>

    <p>
      To find such a value, compute the derivative.
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(x)=3x^2-1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Now solve <m>f'(c)=0</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      3c^2-1=0.
    </me>

    <me>
      3c^2=1.
    </me>

    <me>
      c=\pm\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Of these solutions, only
    </p>

    <me>
      c=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}
    </me>

    <p>
      lies in the interval <m>(0,1)</m>.  Therefore this value satisfies
      the conclusion of Rolle's Theorem.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-mvt-cubic">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=x^3-x, \qquad x\in[1,5].
    </me>

    <p>
      Verify that the Mean Value Theorem applies, and find a value
      <m>c\in(1,5)</m> for which
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(c)=\frac{f(5)-f(1)}{5-1}.
    </me>

  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      The function <m>f(x)=x^3-x</m> is a polynomial, so it is continuous
      for all real numbers and differentiable for all real numbers.
      Therefore it is continuous on the closed interval <m>[1,5]</m>
      and differentiable on the open interval <m>(1,5)</m>.  
      Thus the conditions of the Mean Value Theorem are satisfied.
    </p>

    <p>
      First compute the average rate of change of <m>f</m> on
      <m>[1,5]</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    \frac{f(5)-f(1)}{5-1}
    \amp= \frac{(5^3-5)-(1^3-1)}{4} \\
    \amp= \frac{120-0}{4} \\
    \amp= 30.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Next compute the derivative of <m>f</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(x)=3x^2-1.
    </me>

    <p>
      To find <m>c</m>, solve
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(c)=30.
    </me>

    <me>
      3c^2-1=30.
    </me>

    <me>
      3c^2=31.
    </me>

    <me>
      c=\pm\sqrt{\frac{31}{3}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>c</m> must lie in the interval <m>(1,5)</m>, we discard the
      negative solution.  Therefore
    </p>

    <me>
      c=\sqrt{\frac{31}{3}}\approx 3.21.
    </me>

    <p>
      This value lies in the interval <m>(1,5)</m>, so it satisfies the
      conclusion of the Mean Value Theorem.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-mvt-rational">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=\frac{2x-5}{3x}, \qquad x\in[1,7].
    </me>

    <p>
      Verify that the Mean Value Theorem applies, and find a value
      <m>c\in(1,7)</m> for which
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(c)=\frac{f(7)-f(1)}{7-1}.
    </me>

  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>
      The function <m>f(x)=\frac{2x-5}{3x}</m> is a rational function, so it
      is differentiable wherever the denominator is nonzero.
      Since <m>3x\neq 0</m> for all <m>x\in[1,7]</m>, the function is
      continuous on the closed interval <m>[1,7]</m> and differentiable on
      the open interval <m>(1,7)</m>.
      Therefore the conditions of the Mean Value Theorem are satisfied.
    </p>

    <p>
      First compute the average rate of change of <m>f</m> on the interval.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    \frac{f(7)-f(1)}{7-1}
    \amp=
    \frac{\frac{14-5}{21}-\frac{2-5}{3}}{6} \\[6pt]
    \amp=
    \frac{\frac{9}{21}-(-1)}{6} \\[6pt]
    \amp=
    \frac{\frac{9}{21}+1}{6} \\[6pt]
    \amp=
    \frac{30}{126} \\[6pt]
    \amp=
    \frac{5}{21}.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Next compute the derivative of <m>f</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
    \begin{aligned}
    f'(x)
    \amp=
    \frac{(3x)(2)-(2x-5)(3)}{(3x)^2} \\[6pt]
    \amp=
    \frac{6x-6x+15}{9x^2} \\[6pt]
    \amp=
    \frac{5}{3x^2}.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      To find <m>c</m>, solve
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(c)=\frac{5}{21}.
    </me>

    <me>
      \frac{5}{3c^2}=\frac{5}{21}.
    </me>

    <me>
      21=3c^2.
    </me>

    <me>
      c^2=7.
    </me>

    <me>
      c=\pm\sqrt{7}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>c</m> must lie in the interval <m>(1,7)</m>, we discard the
      negative solution.  Therefore
    </p>

    <me>
      c=\sqrt{7}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>1&lt;\sqrt{7}&lt;7</m>, this value satisfies the conclusion
      of the Mean Value Theorem.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>


    </subsection>


       <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivApp-curve1">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivApp-curve1"/> Curve Sketching Part 1</title>

      
<example xml:id="ex-abs-value-analysis">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x)=5-|x+2|</m>.
    </p>
        <p>
          (a) Find the critical number(s) of <m>f</m>.
        </p>
        <p>         (b) Determine the intervals where <m>f</m> is increasing and decreasing.</p>
          <p>        (c) Find the local maxima and minima of <m>f</m>.</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) First rewrite the absolute value as a piecewise function.
    </p>

    <me>
      f(x)=
      \begin{cases}
      5-(x+2) = 3-x &amp; \text{if } x \ge -2 \\
      5-(-(x+2)) = x+7 &amp; \text{if } x &lt; -2
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      The domain of <m>f</m> is all real numbers.
    </p>

    <p>
      The derivative on each interval is
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(x)=
      \begin{cases}
      -1 &amp; x&gt;-2 \\
      1 &amp; x&lt;-2
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      The derivative does not exist at <m>x=-2</m>, so this is a critical number.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) Since <m>f'(x)&gt;0</m> for <m>x \in (-\infty, -2)</m> and <m>f'(x)&lt;0</m> for <m>x \in (-2, \infty)</m>,
      the function increases on the interval <m>(-\infty, -2)</m> and decreases on the interval <m>(-2, \infty)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) By the First Derivative Test, since <m>f'(x)</m> changes from positive to negative at <m>x=-2</m>, the function has a local maximum 
      at <m>x=-2</m>.
      There are no local minima.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>
      

<example xml:id="ex-increasing-decreasing-cos2x">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider <m>f(x)=\sqrt{2}x+\cos(2x)</m> on the interval <m>[0,\pi]</m>.
    </p>

           <p>
          (a) Find the critical number(s) of <m>f</m>.
        </p>
        <p>         (b) Determine the intervals where <m>f</m> is increasing and decreasing.</p>
          <p>        (c) Find the local maxima and minima of <m>f</m>.</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
   <p> (a) To find the critical numbers, compute the derivative.</p>

    <me>
      f'(x)=\sqrt{2}-2\sin(2x).
    </me>

    <p>
      This is always defined, so the only critical numbers will come from <m>f'(x)=0</m>, solve
    </p>

    <me>\begin{aligned}
      0 \amp = \sqrt{2}-2\sin(2x) \\
      2\sin(2x) \amp = \sqrt{2} \\
      \sin(2x) \amp = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\\ 
      2x \amp = \dfrac{\pi}{4}, \dfrac{3\pi}{4}, \dfrac{9\pi}{4}, \dfrac{11\pi}{4}, \ldots \\
      x \amp = \dfrac{\pi}{8}, \dfrac{3\pi}{8}, \dfrac{9\pi}{8}, \dfrac{11\pi}{8}, \ldots
    \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p> Of these solutions, only <m>x=\frac{\pi}{8}</m> and <m>x=\frac{3\pi}{8}</m> lie in the interval <m>[0,\pi]</m>, 
      so these are the critical numbers.</p>

      <p> (b) To determine where the function is increasing and decreasing, we can use the critical numbers to 
        divide the interval into three subintervals: <m>[0,\frac{\pi}{8})</m>, <m>(\frac{\pi}{8},\frac{3\pi}{8})</m>, 
        and <m>(\frac{3\pi}{8},\pi]</m>.  We can test a point in each interval to determine the sign of the derivative.</p>
        <ul><li> For <m>x=0</m>, <m>f'(0)=\sqrt{2}-2\sin(0)=\sqrt{2}\gt 0</m>, so the function is increasing on <m>[0,\frac{\pi}{8})</m>.</li>
          <li> For <m>x=\frac{\pi}{4}</m>, <m>f'(\frac{\pi}{4})=\sqrt{2}-2\sin(\frac{\pi}{2})=\sqrt{2}-2\lt 0</m>, so the function is decreasing on <m>(\frac{\pi}{8},\frac{3\pi}{8})</m>.</li>
            <li> For <m>x=\pi</m>, <m>f'(\pi)=\sqrt{2}-2\sin(2\pi)=\sqrt{2}\gt 0</m>, so the function is increasing on <m>(\frac{3\pi}{8},\pi]</m>.</li></ul>
    <p> (c) By the First Derivative Test, since <m>f'(x)</m> changes from positive to negative at <m>x=\frac{\pi}{8}</m>, the function has a local maximum at <m>x=\frac{\pi}{8}</m>.  
      Since <m>f'(x)</m> changes from negative to positive at <m>x=\frac{3\pi}{8}</m>, the function has a local minimum at <m>x=\frac{3\pi}{8}</m>.</p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-curve-sketching-exp">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function <m>f(x)=xe^{-x}</m>.
    </p>
    <p> (a) Find the critical number(s) of <m>f</m>.</p>
    <p> (b) Determine the intervals where <m>f</m> is increasing and decreasing.</p>
    <p> (c) Find the local maxima and minima of <m>f</m>.</p>
    <p> (d) Determine the intervals where <m>f</m> is concave up and concave down, and find any inflection points.</p>
    <p> (e) Sketch the graph of <m>f</m> using the information from parts (a)-(d).</p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) To find the critical numbers, compute the derivative. 
    </p>
    <me>
      f'(x)=e^{-x}-xe^{-x}=(1-x)e^{-x}.
    </me>
    <p> This is always defined, so the only critical numbers will come from <m>f'(x)=0</m>, solve
    </p>
    <me>\begin{aligned}
      (1-x)e^{-x} \amp  = 0  \\
      1-x \amp = 0 \\
      1 \amp = x.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>
    <p> Thus the only critical number is <m>x=1</m>.</p>
    <p> (b) To determine where the function is increasing and decreasing, we can use the critical number to 
      divide the interval into two subintervals: <m>(-\infty,1)</m> and <m>(1,\infty)</m>.  We can test a point in each interval to determine the sign of the derivative.</p>
      <ul><li> For <m>x=0</m>, <m>f'(0)=(1-0)e^{0}=1\gt 0</m>, so the function is increasing on <m>(-\infty,1)</m>.</li>
        <li> For <m>x=2</m>, <m>f'(2)=(1-2)e^{-2}=-e^{-2}\lt 0</m>, so the function is decreasing on <m>(1,\infty)</m>.</li></ul>
    <p> (c) By the First Derivative Test, since <m>f'(x)</m> changes from positive to negative at <m>x=1</m>, the function has a local maximum at <m>x=1</m>.  
      There are no local minima.</p>
    <p> (d) To determine where the function is concave up and concave down, compute the second derivative.</p>
    <me>
      f''(x)=-e^{-x}-(1-x)e^{-x}=(x-2)e^{-x}.
    </me>
    <p> This is always defined, so the only points of inflection will come from <m>f''(x)=0</m>, solve
    </p>
    <me>\begin{aligned}
      (x-2)e^{-x} \amp = 0 \\
      x-2 \amp = 0 \\
      x \amp = 2.
    \end{aligned}
    </me>
    <p> To determine the concavity, we can
      divide the interval into two subintervals: <m>(-\infty,2)</m> and <m>(2,\infty)</m>.  We can test a point in each interval to determine the sign of the second derivative.</p>
      <ul><li> For <m>x=0</m>, <m>f''(0)=(0-2)e^{0}=-2\lt 0</m>, so the function is concave down on <m>(-\infty,2)</m>.</li>
        <li> For <m>x=3</m>, <m>f''(3)=(3-2)e^{-3}=e^{-3}\gt 0</m>, so the function is concave up on <m>(2,\infty)</m>.</li></ul>
    <p> Thus the function is concave down on <m>(-\infty,2)</m> and concave up on <m>(2,\infty)</m>, and there is an inflection point at <m>x=2</m>.</p>
    <p> (e) To sketch the graph of <m>f</m>, we can use the information from parts (a)-(d).  
      <ul> 
        <li> <m>f(0)=0\cdot e^{0}=0</m>, so the graph passes through the point <m>(0,0)</m>.</li>
        <li> The function is increasing on <m>(-\infty,1)</m> and decreasing on <m>(1,\infty)</m>. </li>
        <li> There is a local maximum at <m>x=1</m>.</li>
        <li> The function is concave down on <m>(-\infty,2)</m> and concave up on <m>(2,\infty)</m>.</li>
        <li> There is an inflection point at <m>x=2</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p> Combining all this we can sketch the graph of <m>f</m>.</p>

          <image source="images/curveSketch12.png" width="90%">
        <shortdescription>
  A graph of f(x)=xe^(-x). The graph starts at (0,0), increases to a local maximum at x=1, 
  then decreases and has an inflection point at x=2, after which it continues to decrease but is concave up.
        </shortdescription>
      </image>
  </solution>
</example>


    </subsection>


